autious with new money but she’s taking a close look at largecap financial and healthcare companies which could benefit if trump reduces regulations and she sees opportunities in fixed income despite federal reserve tightening “it’s easy to say never buy bonds in a rising interestrate environment but in  there could be opportunities when the market gets ahead of itself” case in point municipal bonds which sold off after the election on trump’s pledge to lower taxes which would make taxfree bonds relatively less attractive than taxable bonds but by year end muni yields were higher than treasuries and the standard  poor’s  —michael sisk «less arizona growing up david stahle spent his summers working for his father’s publishing business at age  he wanted to put some of his earnings into amore» arizona growing up david stahle spent his summers working for his father’s publishing business at age  he wanted to put some of his earnings into a mutual fund but his dad’s broker wouldn’t give him the time of day so his father pulled his account and transferred it to merrill lynch where stahle has spent his career he attended college for a year and a half while interning at merrill when he was  he took his series  exam over christmas break and passed with flying colors prompting his manager to hire him “he took a risk on me even though i was young and didn’t have a college degree” recalls stahle now  and based in the firm’s gilbert office he still follows the lessons he learned early on—to focus on what’s best for clients and put their interests first about  years ago a dying client asked him to continue to check on his wife’s financial wellbeing after he passed—a request stahle honored “i don’t just look at them as clients i look at them as family” he says —cheryl winokur munk «less arkansas as a young teenager allen homra showed no interest when his dad tried to teach him about investing in college however he took a liking to it andmore» arkansas as a young teenager allen homra showed no interest when his dad tried to teach him about investing in college however he took a liking to it and interned at a bond firm where most of the sales were done by phone he decided this wasn’t for him so he pursued opportunities where he could meet clients face to face “i was raised in a small town i’ve always been a person who gets along with people” says homra  who’s been at edward jones since  based in stuttgart ark the financial advisor still owns the bluechip stocks he inherited from his grandfather in the s and he believes in taking a longterm approach for his clients as well “most of my clients have the same philosophies that i have” he says he tries to keep things simple—shying away from complicated investment products that many people would find hard to understand “i know that we make a difference in our clients’ lives that’s very important” he adds —cheryl winokur munk «less california andy chase a former us tennis association junior champion has won in the investment arena too with a simple formula “i’m into riskadjustedmore» california andy chase a former us tennis association junior champion has won in the investment arena too with a simple formula “i’m into riskadjusted returns and i like cash flow” he says hired by smith barney in  chase set up shop in silicon valley to remain near his alma mater stanford “at the time the area was a backwater” he says “but soon venture capital firms would flood in” chase  now works for morgan stanley at its menlo park office he likes health care which has been beaten up “it’s very rare that you get to buy what i think is going to be the fastestgrowing industry with a big global tail wind from aging and demographics” he says “and you’re buying one of the cheaper sectors other than utilities” but he’s skeptical of “america first” themes like defense infrastructure and energy “anyone that makes their investment decisions based on what the government might or might not do is making a mistake” he warns —steve garmhausen «less colorado clients wonder about the effect that donald trump’s trade and taxreform policies will have on the market says shawn fowler managing director inmore» colorado clients wonder about the effect that donald trump’s trade and taxreform policies will have on the market says shawn fowler managing director in morgan stanley private wealth management’s denver office “we are humble enough to say we don’t know” he tells them and then asks “what are your goals what have we built for you and are we on track to achieve those goals” fowler  says his investment strategy has three anchors dividendgrowth stocks highquality municipal bonds and real estate split  between reit index funds and privateequity realty funds these all generate enough cash to ensure that each client’s “standard of living is defensible” this approach has earned him loyalty which he returns his first clients were a couple he coldcalled recently when the husband died fowler traveled to arkansas to help the wife clean out her house and prepare for her next chapter why because “they gave me a chance  years ago” michael sisk «less connecticut jeff erdmann prides himself on serving multiplegeneration households—often with  million or more to invest “our clients consider me and my teammore» connecticut jeff erdmann prides himself on serving multiplegeneration households—often with  million or more to invest “our clients consider me and my team a crucial member of their family as we help satisfy their planning and investment needs” he says erdmann started with merrill lynch in  as a retail broker but he quickly shifted away from a transactional approach after realizing that clients preferred holistic advice now  erdmann is trying to help clients process the flood of news from washington he thinks that tax cuts and repatriation of overseas corporate cash will materialize “however” he observes “a lot of that is already priced into the market” based in merrill’s greenwich office he sees a good chance for low to midsingledigit stock market returns this year but that will depend on the trump team’s effectiveness in implementing its financial agenda says erdmann “we’ll have a much clearer picture in the next three to four months as to how well this administration can execute” —steve garmhausen «less dc it’s not often you get a relief rally when the markets have been up for most of eight years but that’s what marvin mcintyre thinks happened aftermore» dc it’s not often you get a relief rally when the markets have been up for most of eight years but that’s what marvin mcintyre thinks happened after donald trump was elected “the very idea of less regulation and more growth was powerful” says the morgan stanley private wealth management advisor who considers the trump presidency a positive for stocks however some of his clients are less focused on the market than they are on estate planning and quality of life mcintyre recently did a financial review for a client who looked  years older than he is the client it turned out was fighting with his business partner mcintyre  asked what he’d do if he could walk away when the man said he’d love to teach mcintyre said “we’ve just gone over the numbers and you could turn the faucet on here and live comfortably for the rest of your life” two weeks later the client thanked him his partner had agreed to buy him out and he planned to teach in the fall —michael sisk «less delaware perhaps the best bit of early career advice that kimberlee orth received came from her future husband she was in her early s and unsatisfiedmore» delaware perhaps the best bit of early career advice that kimberlee orth received came from her future husband she was in her early s and unsatisfied working in a hospital’s budgeting and reimbursement unit “why don’t you get into financial planning” he suggested “that’s really where the future is” once she became a certified financial planner she loved her new career orth  an ameriprise advisor in wilmington focuses on making sure clients have realistic retirement expectations “look at the budget create a bucket list and dig deeper to understand what you spend now and how much of that spending is likely to continue” she advises she wants both spouses to attend facetoface meetings with her even though one usually takes the lead and is her main contact “it’s good for that other spouse to see the kinds of questions asked and the kinds of answers i give” it gives that individual confidence orth adds should the day come when he or she must be the lead spouse in financial discussions —michael sisk «less florida thomas moran says the us economy is on good footings and that he expects solid earnings this year “the chance of recession is well below average”more» florida thomas moran says the us economy is on good footings and that he expects solid earnings this year “the chance of recession is well below average” observes moran who works for wells fargo advisors in naples that’s particularly good news for small and midcap companies that make most of their profits domestically he adds noting that the stronger dollar will create head winds for large us corporations with significant overseas operations moran  tends to focus on highdividend stocks for income for more adventurous clients he uses exchangetraded funds that invest in alternative assets such as timber water currencies or precious metals he eschews anything with an exit fee or mandatory holding period because his clients generally “are in the distribution phase of their life and it gives them peace of mind that the money is accessible” moran and his wife sandi have cochaired the naples winter wine festival which has raised over  million for children’s charities over the past  years —michael sisk «less georgia the daughter of one of rod westmoreland’s clients recently gave  to a friend to buy a dog because she told her parents “we have so much moneymore» georgia the daughter of one of rod westmoreland’s clients recently gave  to a friend to buy a dog because she told her parents “we have so much money it doesn’t matter” another client told him that she was divorcing her husband of plus years in the first instance westmoreland set up a series of family meetings in the second he suggested a coolingoff period such “soft issues” come with the territory when you work closely with clients of course westmoreland  a managing director at the merrill lynch private banking and investment group in atlanta also keeps a close eye on returns his goal is to achieve inflation plus —not easy in today’s lowinterestrate environment in  he had about  invested in bonds today it’s virtually zero instead he emphasizes us stocks and private equity he’s bullish on corporate profits given possible cuts in taxes and regulations he also likes some european companies with global operations and undervalued shares —michael sisk «less hawaii eric fujimoto was going into accounting until he realized that those college classes started at  am—so he opted for noon classes that led him tomore» hawaii eric fujimoto was going into accounting until he realized that those college classes started at  am—so he opted for noon classes that led him to becoming a financial advisor at age  now he rises at  am to be ready when the new york markets open “kind of ironic” he admits fujimoto  who works for ameriprise financial in honolulu likes simple liquid investments that clients can understand such as midcap largecap growth or value stocks and bonds suited to their risk tolerance currently health care and tech are among the sectors he favors he has clients both in hawaii and on the mainland one difference in the continental us families often are spread over thousands of miles but in hawaii many multigenerational families live “within a stone’s throw” of one another that fosters the socalled ohana spirit of close contact with one’s neighbors fujimoto is part of four generations on the island which connects him to his clients and hel